ts on their merit. They would then be classified as ‘crime’ or ‘non-crime’. If ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crimed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’, they would then be ‘screened in’ or ‘screened out’ depending upon whether or not there were leads to follo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">w. If ‘screened in’ further investigation would follow. My experience (including working on a Crime Desk) suggests that, at this time, crimes were (on the whole) being correctly classified and screened. This had changed significantly toward the end of my p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">olice service – and was a major contributing factor in my decision to leave the police service.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1b) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In 2004 I was working with the NHS to reduce assaults on NHS staff. I clearly recall attending Marylebone Police Station near to Christmas in order to repor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t assaults on NHS staff. I witnessed a police officer listen to a Spanish national make an allegation of robbery (his passport being stolen from his rucksack, by force) and then tell him that he would record it as being ‘lost in the street’. Immediately af</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">terward</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a gentleman came in (at least an octogenarian) to report the theft of his Christmas hamper by his </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">neighbour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – the police officer told him it was a ‘civil matter’ and that he should speak to a solicitor. I was disgusted, but I knew that it was point</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">less to say anything as such action </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by an officer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was now </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">expected</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the police service.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1c) More recently I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have suffered anti-social </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by youths, which was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> regularly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> reported to police by me and my</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> neighbours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The police did nothing. Having witn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">essed the sale and supply of drugs, etc (in the churchyard next door) I again phoned police. They didn’t respond for over 15 minutes and so, when I witnessed a youth damaging the 14</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Century church, I went out and arrested him myself, despite there being </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a gang of 15 youths. The police response was to (eventually) send two women PCSOs!! The police officers that did eventually attend were mightily cheesed off at having to take a youth into custody</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">…..I haven’t heard anything more from the police about the re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sult of the incident from that day to this and having been in touch with the Vicar and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> PCC, they had no knowledge of the citizen’s arrest or the damage – it would appear that the youth was simply ‘let go’ by police, despite first-hand evidence and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a citizen’s arrest having been made.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2. What are the factors which can influence police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-recording of crime?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2a) Currently serving police officers have told me that they are put under pressure by supervising/inspecting ranks not to record crime.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3. Are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function effectively and accurately? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">No. The police are able to say that recorded crime has fallen only because they are the organization responsible for recording it in the first pl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ace.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4. Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4a) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Independent monitoring needs to be in place which compares information received from the public by control rooms, to eventual outcomes. In my day, this gate-k</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eeping function was undertaken by a Control Room Sergeant, who would not ‘close’ any incident where a crime had been alleged with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">out</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a Crime Reference Number ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ving been appended to the call L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">og. Nowadays, all you get is the Log number. For example, I rece</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ntly called police to report an assault and false imprisonment in my employment as a County Court Bailiff. When I was on the phone to police</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> my captors released me and so the police no longer needed to attend immediately</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I haven’t withdrawn my allegation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of crime </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the police have done nothing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to follow up on the allegation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5. To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5a) I believe that policymakers can have little or n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o confidence in the recording of crime statistics by police.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6. Should recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6a) Yes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; and more scrutiny should take place as to what is ‘recorded’ and ‘reported’ crime.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>